      "type": "faq-accordion",
      "blocks": {
        "faq-1": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "question": "How does fixing my gut clear my skin?",
            "answer": "<p>Acne, eczema, and psoriasis are inflammatory skin conditions — not surface problems. The inflammation driving them often originates in a leaky gut. When bacterial populations deplete and the intestinal barrier weakens, bacterial endotoxins (LPS) enter your bloodstream. Your immune system launches an inflammatory response that manifests in the skin through elevated IL-6, TNF-alpha, and IL-17. Origin's strains — particularly L. acidophilus and L. plantarum — restore gut barrier integrity and directly reduce these inflammatory cytokines. When the gut stops leaking, the skin stops flaring.</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq-2": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "question": "How long before I see improvement in my skin?",
            "answer": "<p>Most people notice reduced frequency of flares within 4-6 weeks. The inflammatory cascade takes time to resolve as the gut barrier strengthens and systemic inflammation decreases. Eczema patches often begin fading within 3-4 weeks. Acne frequency and severity typically improve over 4-8 weeks. Psoriasis plaques — which are driven by a more complex immune pathway — often show improvement from 6 weeks onward. The direction of change is consistent; the timeline varies by individual microbiome composition and the severity of barrier disruption.</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq-3": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "question": "Can I keep using my topical treatments while taking Origin?",
            "answer": "<p>Yes. There's no conflict between Origin and topical skincare, prescription treatments, or medications. Continue your current skincare routine while Origin works internally. Many customers find they need topical products less — and eventually stop flaring — as the internal inflammation resolves. Do not discontinue prescription medications without consulting your physician, especially immunosuppressants or biologics.</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq-4": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "question": "Why did my acne or eczema get worse after moving countries?",
            "answer": "<p>Environmental shift and dietary westernization accelerate bacterial depletion — specifically the strains that maintain gut barrier integrity. This is a documented pattern in modern populations. When the gut barrier weakens, inflammatory triggers that previously stayed in your intestines begin entering systemic circulation. Your skin — as the body's largest detoxification organ — absorbs this inflammatory load. Skin conditions that were absent or mild in your home country worsening after migration is a direct signal of microbiome disruption.</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq-5": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "question": "Is the gut-skin connection scientifically established?",
            "answer": "<p>Yes. The gut-skin axis is well-documented in peer-reviewed research. Salem et al. (Journal of Dermatological Science, 2019) demonstrated altered gut microbiome in acne patients. Bowe and Logan (Gut Pathogens, 2011) documented the gut-acne connection specifically in high-stress Western populations. De Pessemier et al. (Microorganisms, 2021) reviewed the evidence across acne, eczema, and psoriasis, confirming that gut microbiome disruption precedes and drives all three conditions through shared inflammatory mechanisms.</p>"
          }
        }
      },
